node.text:
Time is not on Trump's side. The Biden administration saw a major win by passing a bipartisan trillion dollar infrastructure bill that could flood the workforce with thousands of jobs and keep his campaign promise to fix Washington. Since losing the 2020 election, the former president has had a handful of botched attempts to return to the spotlight. 

Ryan Lizza breaks down the dynamics of Trump's return, what's working, what isn't and what to expect next.

node.title: Trump's influence keeps haunting Washington, explained

node.text:
A year after New York Gov. Andrew Cuomo reached new political heights with daily news briefings that enraptured a nation in the throes of a once-in-a-lifetime pandemic, the three-term Democrat announced plans to resign amid growing pressure to leave or face impeachment over allegations that he sexually harassed nearly a dozen women.

“Given the circumstances, the best way I can help now is if I step aside and let the government get back to government,” Cuomo said in a video statement. “Therefore that's what I'll do, because I work for you, and doing the right thing, is doing the right thing for you. Because, as we say, ‘it's not about me, it's about we.’” 

Read more at the link in bio.

https://politi.co/2UaCHK6

node.title: Andrew Cuomo resigns amid sexual harassment scandal

Manhattan District Attorney Cy Vance’s criminal charges against the Trump Organization don’t just create legal jeopardy for the former president’s company. They also could damage its business interests — regardless of whether or not a jury ultimately finds the company guilty.

Reporter Betsy Woodruff Swan takes a closer look at the Trump Organization indictment and the numbers that matter. https://politi.co/3wCgTUM

White House press secretary Jen Psaki forcefully defended the Biden administration’s growing offensive on vaccine-related misinformation spreading on Facebook and other social media platforms.

“For how long has the administration been spying on people’s Facebook profiles looking for vaccine misinformation?” Fox News’ Peter Doocy asked, referencing Psaki’s comments a day prior that roughly a dozen people on Facebook were responsible for the bulk of vaccine misinformation on the social network.

Psaki called the characterization “a loaded and inaccurate question.” She said that the concerning posts that the White House flagged to platforms like Facebook is similar to the outreach officials have with news outlets when they take issue with particular coverage. Read more at the link in bio.

node.text:
Texas Governor Greg Abbott lacks his predecessors’ star power. He’s constantly dodging attacks from the right. His state is facing another Covid surge. Yet nobody is even close to him in the governor’s race.

What explains Abbott’s grip on power in the country’s biggest red state? The answer is less about the sober-mannered version of Abbott that most Texans know. Instead, it's about the behind-the-scenes version of Abbott : a former Texas Supreme Court justice and attorney general who has learned to adapt to Texas’ changing Republican electorate and anticipate potential political threats.

In a state that has a history of larger-than-life political characters, the two-term Texas governor is a ruthless backstage operator, maintaining a massive field operation and maneuvering among the state’s disparate GOP factions.

With a 2022 election more than a year away, Abbott is now in the midst of another round of navigating between primary and general election voters. Link in bio for more. 

📷: @tamirhasacellphone

When New York Governor Andrew Cuomo announced his resignation this week, the woman who will succeed him, Lieutenant Governor Kathy Hochul, pledged to clean up the “toxic work environment” that had flourished under Cuomo. 

But the women in New York politics and government — politicians and staffers, current and former — are not sure it will be so easy. They say the culture — of harassment, of sexism, of bullying, of protecting those in power — goes so much deeper than Cuomo. Read more at the link in bio.

node.text:
The percentage of American families with kids who report not having enough to eat fell dramatically after the first child tax credit payments were distributed last month.

The government’s finding shows that the monthly payments are having a major and immediate impact on millions of households, potentially bolstering Biden’s push to extend the tax credit past the end of this year.

Before the first tax credit payments hit bank accounts in mid-July, about 11% of households with children reported that they sometimes or often did not have enough to eat. After the money went out, the rate dropped to just over 8% —  the lowest rate recorded since the beginning of the pandemic.

The most recent survey data shows that 47% of households reported spending their tax credit payment on food.

Researchers say it's too early to fully understand the drop in hunger rates, but it seems to be tied to the child tax credit payments. Households with children saw a major decline, while adults in households with no children saw virtually no change over the same period. Link in bio for more. 

📷: Getty 

https://politi.co/3lXkI58

node.text:
The Census Bureau has released the most detailed data from last year’s decennial count, painting a picture of a more diverse America increasingly clustered in and near cities.

The data provides states with the tools to begin the once-a-decade process of redistricting, with both parties eager to fight for favorable political maps in the battle for control of the House of Representatives and state legislatures throughout the country.

Altogether, the maps could tilt control of Congress for the next decade, but they’ll come out one-by-one at first. Strategists from both parties predict that some states will finalize maps as soon as September and that roughly half of the states will set their new lines by the end of the year. The rest will follow in the first few months of 2022. Link in bio for more.

node.text:
The FDA on Thursday will authorize third doses of Pfizer and Moderna's Covid-19 vaccines for people with weakened immune systems, in a bid to bolster their protection against infection as the highly contagious Delta variant circulates.

The policy will only apply to a narrow slice of adults with immune-weakening conditions who may not have gotten adequate protection from the initial two-dose Pfizer or Moderna regimen as a result, a source said. It also does not allow for extra doses of vaccine to be given to immunocompromised people who originally received Johnson & Johnson's one-dose Covid-19 shot.

The CDC's vaccine advisory panel will meet Friday to examine the latest data on extra doses for people with weakened immune systems. The committee is expected to vote to formally recommend the practice — an important endorsement of the FDA's expected decision, but not one that is required before extra doses can be administered. Read more at the link in bio.

Time is not on Trump's side. The Biden administration saw a major win by passing a bipartisan trillion dollar infrastructure bill that could flood the workforce with thousands of jobs and keep his campaign promise to fix Washington. Since losing the 2020 election, the former president has had a handful of botched attempts to return to the spotlight. 

Ryan Lizza breaks down the dynamics of Trump's return, what's working, what isn't and what to expect next.

node.text:
New York Lt. Gov. Kathy Hochul may not be a household name like her boss, Gov. Andrew Cuomo, but in many ways she has been the most visible elected official in New York since she assumed her current role six years ago. 

With Cuomo on Tuesday announcing his resignation effective in two weeks, Hochul will soon become New York’s first female governor, holding the position for the remainder of Cuomo’s third term, which expires at the end of next year. 

The Buffalo native is renowned for putting in grueling hours cutting ribbons, campaigning for down-ballot Democrats and cheerleading for upstate businesses. Now, she has a fine line to walk preparing take the helm amid a resurgent wave of the pandemic. Republicans and conservatives are already launching attacks questioning what she knew about the governor’s misconduct and his coverup of nursing home deaths, presumably preparing for the possibility that she could win the Democratic nomination in the coming gubernatorial race. Read more at the link in bio.

node.text:
A majority of voters support mandatory coronavirus vaccines and indoor mask-wearing requirements. 

According to a new Morning Consult/POLITICO poll, 61% of voters either strongly or somewhat support local governments requiring vaccines for employees in their area. 

The survey also found that about half of all voters blame the new wave of infections on the unvaccinated and on political leaders opposed to mask-wearing and social-distancing mandates.

The poll points to a clear partisan split in perceptions of government’s role in managing the pandemic: around 8 in 10 Democrats want to require vaccines for all Americans (except those with medical conditions) while only roughly 35 percent of Republicans do. Link in bio for more.

A year after New York Gov. Andrew Cuomo reached new political heights with daily news briefings that enraptured a nation in the throes of a once-in-a-lifetime pandemic, the three-term Democrat announced plans to resign amid growing pressure to leave or face impeachment over allegations that he sexually harassed nearly a dozen women.

“Given the circumstances, the best way I can help now is if I step aside and let the government get back to government,” Cuomo said in a video statement. “Therefore that's what I'll do, because I work for you, and doing the right thing, is doing the right thing for you. Because, as we say, ‘it's not about me, it's about we.’”

node.text:
Marijuana has never been more popular in the U.S. — and its carbon emissions have never posed a bigger threat to the climate.

America’s patchwork approach to legalization has helped make cannabis one of the most energy-intensive crops in the nation. And as states embrace marijuana, a growing source of greenhouse gases is going largely unnoticed by climate hawks on Capitol Hill.

Complicating matters further, federal laws also bar cannabis from crossing state lines. That means companies have to grow it in each state where they want to do business, depriving them of the scale that makes other industries more efficient.

"For being such a 'green' industry, there’s some skeletons in the closet," said Kaitlin Urso, an environmental consultant with the Colorado Department of Public Health and Environment.

Despite piecemeal attempts by states and some growers to reduce their power consumption, at least one expert estimates the industry’s footprint already accounts for more than 1 percent of U.S. electricity consumption and continues to rise. Complicating matters further, federal laws also bar the flow of weed over state lines. That requires companies to grow cannabis in each state where they want to do business and deprives them of the scale that makes other industries more efficient.

Biden and Democratic leaders have made cutting the nation’s carbon footprint a top priority. Biden wants to reach net-zero emissions by 2050, and his plan pinpoints agricultural and industrial emissions as targets for reduction. 

Despite the huge climate impact of the nation’s fastest-growing new industry, Biden, most lawmakers and many environmental groups, even those supportive of cannabis legalization, have largely ignored the issue. Link in bio for more.

node.text:
New York Gov. Andrew Cuomo plans to resign amid public pressure from fellow Democrats. This comes after a report from the state attorney general’s office detailed allegations into how he sexually harassed 11 women.

“The best way I can help now is if I step aside,” Cuomo said. He plans to step aside in 14 days.

The three-term governor, who gained national acclaim for his handling of the pandemic, now faces several criminal probes into his alleged conduct. Cuomo had denied the report’s findings, arguing that his accusers misconstrued well-intentioned gestures and comments.

Lt. Gov. Kathy Hochul, a Democrat, is next in the line of succession. Link in bio for more.
